    <tax:treatment obkms_id="1dc82991-28b1-4af9-bddb-41a1809b064a" obkms_process="TRUE">
      <tax:nomenclature obkms_id="4503d11f-b7e8-425a-af7c-e53684e87026" obkms_process="TRUE">Genus<tax:name obkms_id="78885dcd-1566-461e-a169-603433c3f4ce" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Polychaeta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Sabellida</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Sabellidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Perkinsiana</dwc:Genus><dwc:taxonRank>genus</dwc:taxonRank><dwc:scientificNameAuthorship>Knight-Jones, 1983</dwc:scientificNameAuthorship></tax:xmldata>PerkinsianaKnight-Jones, 1983</tax:name>
</tax:nomenclature>
      <tax:div type="discussion" obkms_id="16bc9c3e-f4d5-48be-b1e0-2e545ef18779" obkms_process="TRUE">
        <tax:p>Remarks. The genus<tax:name obkms_id="76af6c8f-dd73-4ba7-ba73-99f180cf28a7" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Polychaeta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Sabellida</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Sabellidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Perkinsiana</dwc:Genus><dwc:taxonRank>genus</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>Perkinsiana</tax:name> was established byKnight-Jones (1983), in order to accommodate species previously assigned to the genera<tax:name obkms_id="68937f4e-9335-448a-8c66-9eee0466a788" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Coleoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Cerambycidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Demonax</dwc:Genus><dwc:taxonRank>genus</dwc:taxonRank><dwc:scientificNameAuthorship>Kinberg, 1867</dwc:scientificNameAuthorship></tax:xmldata>DemonaxKinberg, 1867</tax:name> (=<tax:name obkms_id="3be8a5dd-79ab-446b-87fd-1b232a196a17" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Polychaeta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Sabellida</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Sabellidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Parasabella</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>fide</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank><dwc:scientificNameAuthorship>Tovar-Hernandez &amp; Harris 2010</dwc:scientificNameAuthorship></tax:xmldata>Parasabella fideTovar-Hernández &amp; Harris 2010</tax:name>),<tax:name obkms_id="1ea97593-8f3f-4cf1-a8d7-ce2fc872f229" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Polychaeta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Sabellida</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Sabellidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Potamilla</dwc:Genus><dwc:taxonRank>genus</dwc:taxonRank><dwc:scientificNameAuthorship>Malmgren, 1866</dwc:scientificNameAuthorship></tax:xmldata>PotamillaMalmgren, 1866</tax:name>, and<tax:name obkms_id="d07ffeaa-4e43-451e-83f8-d8a9c42bae45" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Polychaeta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Sabellida</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Sabellidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Potamethus</dwc:Genus><dwc:taxonRank>genus</dwc:taxonRank><dwc:scientificNameAuthorship>Chamberlin, 1919</dwc:scientificNameAuthorship></tax:xmldata>PotamethusChamberlin, 1919</tax:name>.Fitzhugh (1989) provided a diagnosis slightly modified from that ofKnight-Jones (1983) and indicated the genus was not united by any recognized synapomorphies,Capa (2007) amended the genus and, based on a cladistic analysis, she concluded that<tax:name obkms_id="a6aa2a69-b077-4a5f-a218-77c0c3919529" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Polychaeta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Sabellida</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Sabellidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Perkinsiana</dwc:Genus><dwc:taxonRank>genus</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>Perkinsiana</tax:name> is paraphyletic.Tovar-Hernándezet al. (2012) amended the generic diagnosis of<tax:name obkms_id="f21c9e35-e5c8-4394-ab07-6df710da343a" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Polychaeta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Sabellida</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Sabellidae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Perkinsiana</dwc:Genus><dwc:taxonRank>genus</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>Perkinsiana</tax:name>, to include the presence of a palmate membrane and radiolar flanges, and three patterns of abdominal notochaetae: type A) chaetae with a broad hood, progressively tapering to distal tips in all chaetigers; type B) with a broad knee, distal ends narrowing abruptly on all chaetigers; and type C) elongate, with a narrow hood.</tax:p>
        <tax:p>
          <tax:collection_event><tax:xmldata><dwc:Country>Uruguay, Argentina</dwc:Country><dwc:Locality>South America</dwc:Locality></tax:xmldata>In this study, Perkinsiana antarctica ( Kinberg, 1867 ) and Perkinsiana assimilis ( McIntosh, 1885 ) are redescribed and reported for several localities off Uruguay, Argentina and Chile . Sabella magalhaensisKinberg, 1867 is transferred to Perkinsiana , and P. littoralisHartman, 1967 is synonymized to it. Perkinsiana antarctica was found in intertidal zones; P. assimilis , from 90–500 m depth, and P. magalhaensis , from 3–20 m depth. Six species of Perkinsiana from South America are currently valid ( Table 2 ).</tax:collection_event>
        </tax:p>
      </tax:div>
